As Joshua wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/08/2004 at 02:16:39 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>I randomly punched in 2^ln(x) into my TI-89, and the calculator gave 
>me back x^ln(2). How is this possible? Is there a more general case?
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>

Hi Joshua.

thanks for writing to the Math Forum.

Note the following property of exponents:  ln(a^u) = u ln a.
From this, raise e to both sides to obtain

   a^u = e^(u ln a).

Now let a=2 and u=ln(x), and see where that leads you.

- Doctor Douglas, The Math Forum
  <http://mathforum.org/dr.math/>

